    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-03-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-03-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="352"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d352">
                <head>352. Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of Defense for International
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_WP1" type="from">Warnke</persName>) to
                    the Deputy Secretary of Defense (<persName corresp="#p_NPH1" type="to"
                        >Nitze</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d352fn1">Source:
                        Washington National Records Center, RG 330, <gloss target="#t_OASDISA1"
                            >OASD/ISA</gloss> Files: FRC 72 A 1499, Laos 000.1—(Laos 381), 1968. Top
                        Secret; Sensitive. Drafted by Mobley.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">I–35319/68</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-03-28">March 28, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Prairie Fire—Phase III</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Joint Chiefs of Staff have withdrawn their April 1967 proposal for
                    recruiting, training and employing up to 3,000 Kha tribal personnel in the
                        <gloss target="#t_PrairieFire1">Prairie Fire</gloss> area of Laos (Tab
                        A).<note n="2" xml:id="d352fn2">See <ref target="#d282">Document
                        282</ref>.</note> The Joint Staff (<gloss target="#t_SACSA1">SACSA</gloss>)
                    determined in December 1967 to abandon this program after it became clear
                    through our diplomatic channels that the Royal Lao Government was insistent upon
                    the proposed program being under the command and direction of the Lao Armed
                    Forces, instead of being under <gloss target="#t_MACV1">MACV</gloss>.</p>
                <p>The current <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> paper<note n="3" xml:id="d352fn3"
                        >JCSM–170–68, March 21, attached, but not printed.</note> is designed to
                    apprise <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss> and the Department of State
                    officially of the close-out of the <gloss target="#t_PrairieFire1">Prairie
                        Fire</gloss> Phase III proposal and to indicate that some intelligence
                    collection features of the Phase III proposal are included in a separate <gloss
                        target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> recommendation (JCSM–171–68).<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d352fn4">Dated March 21. (Washington National Records Center, RG
                        330, <gloss target="#t_OASDISA1">OASD/ISA</gloss> Files: FRC 72 A 1499, Laos
                        000.1—(381 Laos) For the substance of the proposal, see <ref
                            target="#d353fn2">footnote 2, Document 353</ref>.</note> The latter is
                    now being coordinated with the Department of State.</p>
                <p>Recommend you sign the attached draft memorandum<note n="5" xml:id="d352fn5"
                        >Attached, but not printed.</note> to the Under Secretary of State.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Paul C. Warnke</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="6" xml:id="d352fn6">Printed from a copy that indicates <persName
                                corresp="#p_WP1">Warnke</persName> signed the original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
